What is the structure of your dataset?

The dataset consists of 13 variables and approximately 5000 observations.All the variables are either int or num datatype. Summary statistics doesn’t help in distribution of data and identifying patterns. So in the next section the distribution of each feature is plotted.

The fixed acidity seems to be centered with some outliers to the right. The bin width has been reduced to get more details into the distribution

The volatile acidity is slightly skewed to the right with few outliers.

The distribution of citric acid looks centred with few outliers to the right. With a binwidth of 0.01 we can see that there are quite a few wines at citric acid =0.5 which is quite unlikely.

The plot with a binwidth=0.5 we see that almost half the wines have residual sugar in the lower range i.e., 0.5-2. In bivariate and multivariate analysis we will see how this amount affects the quality of wines.

The distribution of chlorides is skewed to the right with significant number of chlorides.

The plot is centred around 40 with few outliers to the right.

The plot is centred around 150 with almost no outliers

Most of the wines have density in the range of 0.98-1.00. In future, we will explore the variations in density and how it is related to other physicochemical features.

pH values show that all white wines are acidic in nature and is quite normally distributed.

The distribution of sulphates seem to be quite normally distributed however it has quite a few outliers to the right.

The bulk of the data seems to be distributed b/w 9-13 % of alcohol with no outliers.

From the above plots we can say that most of the values are centered and quite a few of them have outliers. The histogram quality shows that it has discrete values and could e treated as a factor for future analysis.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main feature of interest in the dataset is the quality of wines.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

11 physicochemical features are responsible for the quality of the wine. I am guessing that the features which are responsible for the taste, smell or after-effect of a wine could impact the quality score of the wine. Volatile acidity, citric acid, residual sugar, free sulfur dioxide, and alcohol are the features in the textfile on the dataset. In the next section the correlation of every feature against quality is estimated.

It would be worthwhile to see the spread of individual variables and how they compare with each other. Therefore, the following boxplot is presented in a normalized scale since the units of each value was different.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

No.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

I started the univariate analysis by plotting histograms of every feature. For most of the features the distribution looked approximately normal with some outliers. It was found that boxplots could be better to compare the features with each other. However, the scales of the features were different, therefore, the dataset was first normalized within the range of 0-1 then boxplots were created.

It can be noted that the chlorides had the lowest spread of data and alcohol has no outliers (is it regulated?)

Bivariate Analysis

There are around 12 features in the dataset and it would be impractical to analyse all the relationship in details. Therefore, a combined bivariate plot is plotted for all the variables using ggpairs. From this plot the variables having strong correlation are further explored in the upcoming sections.

Bivariate Plots Section

From the above plot we can see that there is a strong correlation b/w density and residual sugar, and alcohol and density. We also see moderate correlations b/w quality and volatile acidity, residual sugar, chloride, Total sulfur dioxide, density, and alcohol. These correlations are explored in the next sections.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

As noted volatile acidity has negative correlation with quality.

It is noted that most of the high quality wines (8-9) are less sweet and has sugar content in the range of 1-10.

There is a very weak correlation between total SO2 and quality of wine and most of the wines have SO2 content in the range of 10-50.

Alcohol content had a positive effect on the quality of wine(0.467) which was expected however, the negative correlation of density and quality was interesting which implied dense wines are less preferred. It would be interesting to note the impact of the interacting features on quality which would be carried out in the next section.

Strong relationship is noted between the alcohol and density which is a negative one (-0.792). The reason could be the lower density of alcohol as compared to water so higher the alcohol content in a wine lower would be the density of the wine.

The total sulphur dioxide and the free sulphur dioxide has a moderate corelation of 0.6 which is justified as the latter is a constituent of the former.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relationship is found between density and residual sugar (0.842).

Multivariate Analysis

In this section the effect of alcohol on quality is analysed in conjuction with other features which are correlated to quality (cor>0.1) either positively or negatively.

2 types of plots are made for the input and output features in which the first plot has quality encoded as color and second one has quality faceted. The color encoded plots show us the spread of physicochemical properties for different qualities of wine. On the other hand when quality is faceted we have clearer details on quality of wines.

Multivariate Plots Section

The plot with quality encoded as color shows that most of the wines with quality 6-9 are within 0.2-0.4. However, it is interesting to note that some wines with volatile acidity >0.4 are either very high quality or very poor based on their alcohol content. This fact is further elaborated in the next plot.

In the above 2 plots it is again justified that alcohol content drives the quailty of wine. However, we can see few outliers to this theory, since we see some wine of very high quality with high sugar and low alcohol. This leads to a downward trend in the quality faceted plot. One possible reason for this could be judges with liking for sweet wine rating the wines.

The variation in chloride content is low and is basically limited around 0.05. We can see that higher alcohol content leads to higher rating. Some wines with higher chlorides are of poor quality.

The Sulfur dioxide content is spread across a wide range from 50-200 and a clear trend is visible–higher the alcohol, higher the quality. Some outliers outside the given SO2 range are of very poor quality.

Since alcohol content and density is negatively correlated we see a downward trend in quality too. Higher the alcohol content lower will be the density and lower alcohol content reduces the quality of wine. However, we can see some high quality wines with higher density and low alcohol. These might be the sweet wines (high residual sugar) judged by judges liking for sweeter wine.

Both pH and sulphates are positively correlated with quality and increase in alcohol content further enhances the quality. This fact is noted the plots where higher quantities of the physicochemical components result in higher quality of wine.

In this plot all the features postively correlated with quality are plotted together. We can see that one of the feature balances the effect of other with alcohol having the most impact.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?

Almost all the high quality wine i.e., with a rating 9 had alcohol content greater than 12. Similarly, almost all the wines with poor rating i.e., 3 had an alcohol content less than 12. Alcohol content strengthend almost all the features which had a negative correlation with quality.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

Since alcohol is the parameter which would push a wine towards a better quality rating therefore, we can expect a positive slope linear fit line as noted in plot of alcohol vs volatile acidity. It means that higher the amount of less preferred chemical higher the alcohol needed in order to maintain a high rating. However, in the following plots a negative slope is observed implying even though the amount of alcohol decreased and the unwanted chemical composition increased, the quality rating didn’t drop.

OPTIONAL: Did you create any models with your dataset? Discuss the strengths and limitations of your model.

I tried to fit a linear model into the dataset. The outliers tend to sway the best fit line. ——

Final Plots and Summary

From the analysis, I found that alcohol percentage is the most important factor affecting the quality of the wine. The relationship of alcohol with quality and how it is strengthened by other positively correlated factors are explained in the following section.

Plot One

Description One

The plot of counts of alcohol % by volume shows that majority of wines have alcohol percentage below 12% yet most of the highly rated wines have more than 12% alcohol. It is also interesting to note that there are no outliers in the data which means that it might be regulated.

Plot Two

Description Two

This plot shows the positive correlation between alcohol percentage and quality of wine. The linear relationship asserts the fact.The important thing to note is most of the wines with rating 8 and above has alcohol percentage greater than 12 % by volume.

Plot Three

Description Three

The above plot shows the impact of 3 positively correlated features on the feature of interest. It is worthwhile to note that all the plots have a downward slope which signifies that decrease in amount of feature is balanced by increasein other feature to retain the quality of wine.
